    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Murphy's story</h2>
      <p>Murphy had mammary cancer. She also had a brief period of hyperthyroidism before the cancer diagnosis — a reminder that senior cats rarely present with just one thing, and each condition changes the picture. We went through chemotherapy with her. It didn't help. Her vet recommended stopping aggressive treatment when it became clear the treatment was causing suffering without benefit, and we agreed. That was the right call. It was also one of the hardest.</p>
      <p>What we learned through Murphy: a cancer diagnosis opens a lot of conversations that vets don't always initiate. Curative versus palliative goals. Second opinions. What the realistic best case looks like. When to stop. These are conversations you have to ask for — and they are the ones that matter most.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>The distinction that changes everything:</strong> There is a significant difference between a vet who says "there's nothing more we can do" when there are actually more options, and a vet who says "more treatment is likely to cause more suffering than benefit." Learning to distinguish those two situations — and having the conversations that help you understand which one you're in — is what advocacy looks like here.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask whether the goal is curative or palliative — and be explicit about it.</strong> These require different decisions. If you don't know which goal you're working toward, ask your vet to name it directly.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about staging.</strong> Understanding whether cancer has spread affects every downstream decision. What imaging has been done? What does it show?</li>
        <li><strong>Don't wait on lumps.</strong> A lump that has been stable for a while can still be malignant. The only way to know is cytology or biopsy. Ask for it rather than monitoring.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about a specialist referral.</strong> Veterinary oncologists exist. If you're facing a significant treatment decision, a consultation is reasonable. This is not distrust of your regular vet — it is appropriate due diligence.</li>
        <li><strong>When a vet recommends stopping treatment, ask for the reasoning explicitly.</strong> "What specifically has led to this recommendation? If we continued, what is the realistic best case?" You are entitled to understand the decision, not just receive it.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask what comfort care looks like from wherever you are.</strong> Whether treatment is ongoing or has ended, palliative care is a legitimate and specific plan — not just "keeping them comfortable." Ask what it involves.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

